The proposed system adopts a layered web-based architecture consisting of a user interface, backend application logic, database, and supporting modules for calculation, visualisation and ranking. This structure was chosen to maintain clear separation of concerns while keeping the system simple and manageable within the scope of the project.
The decision to use a single backend service rather than a distributed or microservices approach was deliberate. Given the scale of the Health Tracker system and its intended role as a business experiment, a monolithic structure reduces complexity, simplifies deployment and improves maintainability. Introducing microservices at this stage would increase development overhead without providing significant architectural benefit.
The database design stores only raw, timestamped health entries rather than derived values such as daily totals, trends or ranking positions. These derived metrics are calculated dynamically when requested. This approach avoids data redundancy, reduces the risk of inconsistency, and ensures that edits or deletions immediately reflect in summaries and leaderboards. While dynamic calculation may introduce minor processing overhead, the limited dataset size and defined date ranges make this trade-off acceptable within the current system scope.
Security and privacy considerations influenced several design decisions. All sensitive health data is stored securely and transmitted via HTTPS. Ranking data is restricted to authenticated users and limited to accepted friends only. These measures align with non-functional requirements relating to data protection and ensure that personal health information is not exposed unnecessarily.
The ranking system uses weekly workout count as the default metric in order to directly satisfy the acceptance criteria. Additional ranking modes, such as calorie totals or weighted scores, are designed as optional extensions rather than core dependencies. This ensures that the system meets required functionality while remaining flexible for future enhancement.
Certain features were intentionally excluded from the current design. Integration with wearable devices, third-party health APIs and native mobile applications were considered out of scope to prevent over-engineering and maintain focus on core behaviours. These integrations could be introduced in future iterations if the system were to expand beyond its experimental phase.
Looking ahead, the architecture allows for future evolution without major structural changes. For example, external API integration could be added through additional service layers, and performance optimisation techniques such as caching could be introduced if data volume increases. The modular separation between calculation, ranking and visualisation components supports this potential scalability.
Overall, the design prioritises clarity, maintainability and alignment with user stories over unnecessary complexity. The chosen architecture realistically supports the required behaviours while remaining adaptable for future development.
